,"1280":"1280","about 1329":"circa 1329","1368":"1368","1357":"1357","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","Abt 1320":"circa 1320","1276":"1276","1320":"1320","1307":"1307","1329":"1329","Lower Booths, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lower Booths, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1276–1350":"1276–1350","1275–1357":"1275–1357","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","1280–1307":"1280–1307","–Female":"Deceased","1280–1370":"1280–1370","1320–1368":"1320–1368","1329–1390":"1329–1390","1202–1275":"1202–1275","1242–Female":"1242–Deceased","before 1320":"before 1320","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1280":"1280","about 1329":"about 1329","1368":"1368","1357":"1357","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1276":"1276","1320":"1320","1307":"1307","1329":"1329","Lower Booths, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lower Booths, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Notton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Barton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred 